 inland ports. 
LOOP handles 13 percent of the nation's foreign oil, about 1.2 million barrels a day, and connects by pipeline to 50 percent of the U.S. <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../137/195137.xml">
refining</link> capability.<p>

Tankers offload at LOOP by pumping crude oil through hoses connected to a Single Point Mooring (SPM) base.  Three SPMs are located 8,000 feet (2.4 km) from the Marine Terminal. The SPMs are designed to handle ships up to 700,000 <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../360/4709360.xml">
deadweight</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../318/30318.xml">
ton</link>s (635,000 metric <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../185/31185.xml">
tonne</link>s). The crude oil then moves to the Marine Terminal via a 56-<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../775/14775.xml">
inch</link> (1.4 <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../947/18947.xml">
meter</link>) diameter submarine <invention wordnetid="105633385" confidence="0.8">
<gossip wordnetid="107223170" confidence="0.8">
<grapevine wordnetid="107223635" confidence="0.8">
<event wordnetid="100029378" confidence="0.8">
<informing wordnetid="107212190" confidence="0.8">
<report wordnetid="107217924" confidence="0.8">
<act wordnetid="100030358" confidence="0.8">
<psychological_feature wordnetid="100023100" confidence="0.8">
<speech_act wordnetid="107160883" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../111/51111.xml">
pipeline</link></speech_act>
</psychological_feature>
</act>
</report>
</informing>
</event>
</grapevine>
</gossip>
